do &lt;action(1;2;3)&gt; ?[/quote:tukfn5g1]

That looks right, though I have a clue why you can't get it to work, but first here's a quick 'proof of concept' that shows a string variable, a numeric variable and a literal being passed to a procedure.


[code:tukfn5g1]' Quest 3&#46;5 ASL Template


define game &lt;Game Name&gt;

	asl-version &lt;350&gt;

	gametype singleplayer

	game version &lt;1&#46;0&gt;
	game author &lt;Your Name&gt;
	game copyright &lt;Â© 2004 &#46;&#46;&#46;&gt;
	game info &lt;Enter any additional information about this game here&#46;&gt;

	start &lt;Start Room&gt;

end define

define room &lt;Start Room&gt;

	look &lt;A start room&gt;
	script &#123;
	set numeric &lt;count;5&gt;
	set string &lt;descrip;widgets&gt;
	do &lt;test&#40;9;%count%;#descrip#&#41;&gt;
	&#125;
end define

define procedure &lt;test&gt;
	set string &lt;stuff;&gt;
	set &lt;stuff;The $parameter&#40;1&#41;$ $parameter&#40;3&#41;$ are in $parameter&#40;2&#41;$ boxes&gt;
	msg &lt;#stuff#&gt;
end define

define text &lt;intro&gt;
Enter intro text here
end define

define text &lt;win&gt;
Enter win text here
end define

define text &lt;lose&gt;
Enter lose text here
end define[/code:tukfn5g1]

So procedures can be passed parameters - but (and I don't know why) if you try calling the above procedure direct from the 'look' in its alternative style, it fails.  Very weird 'bug', but it could easily lead you to think procedures with params don't work at all, when actually they do - mostly <!-- s:shock: --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_eek.gif" alt=":shock:" title="Shocked" /><!-- s:shock: --> 

